  "modules": [
    {
      "title": "What is a wave?",
      "html": "<p>A <b>wave</b> is a disturbance that transfers energy through a medium (or space, for EM waves) without net movement of the medium itself.</p><h4>Terms</h4><ul><li><b>Amplitude (A)</b>: maximum displacement.</li><li><b>Wavelength (λ)</b>: distance between two successive similar points.</li><li><b>Period (T)</b>: time for one complete cycle.</li><li><b>Frequency (f)</b>: cycles per second, Hz, f = 1/T.</li><li><b>Speed</b>: v = fλ.</li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "A wave: f=50 Hz, λ=6 m. Speed?",
          "a": "v = 50·6 = 300 m/s."
        },
        {
          "q": "Period of a 200 Hz wave?",
          "a": "T = 1/200 = 5 ms."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Transverse and longitudinal waves",
      "html": "<p><b>Transverse</b>: particles vibrate perpendicular to the direction of propagation. Examples: water waves, waves on strings, all electromagnetic waves.</p><p><b>Longitudinal</b>: particles vibrate parallel to the direction of propagation, producing compressions and rarefactions. Example: sound waves in air.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Sound is which type of wave?",
          "a": "Longitudinal."
        },
        {
          "q": "Are light waves transverse or longitudinal?",
          "a": "Transverse."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Wave properties",
      "html": "<ul><li><b>Reflection</b>: bouncing off a surface; angle of incidence = angle of reflection.</li><li><b>Refraction</b>: change of direction when wave enters a new medium; caused by change in speed. n₁ sin θ₁ = n₂ sin θ₂.</li><li><b>Diffraction</b>: bending around obstacles or through openings, most obvious when the opening ≈ wavelength.</li><li><b>Interference</b>: superposition of two coherent waves — constructive (crest + crest) or destructive (crest + trough).</li><li><b>Polarisation</b>: restricting vibrations to a single plane; only transverse waves can be polarised.</li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Which property proves that light is transverse?",
          "a": "Polarisation."
        },
        {
          "q": "When two crests meet at a point, what type of interference occurs?",
          "a": "Constructive."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Sound waves and air columns",
      "html": "<p>Sound needs a material medium; cannot travel through a vacuum. Speed in air ≈ 340 m/s at 20 °C; faster in liquids and solids.</p><h4>Pitch, quality, intensity</h4><ul><li><b>Pitch</b>: how high/low a note sounds; depends on frequency.</li><li><b>Loudness/Intensity</b>: depends on amplitude.</li><li><b>Quality/Timbre</b>: distinguishes notes of same pitch from different instruments; depends on overtones.</li></ul><h4>Air columns</h4><p>Closed pipe (one end closed): fundamental frequency f = v/(4L); harmonics: odd multiples.<br>Open pipe: f = v/(2L); all harmonics present.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Fundamental frequency of a 0.5 m open pipe, v=340 m/s?",
          "a": "f = 340/(2·0.5) = 340 Hz."
        },
        {
          "q": "Same length closed pipe?",
          "a": "f = 340/(4·0.5) = 170 Hz."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
